<text>In mathematical analysis, the Minkowski inequality establishes that the L&quot;p&quot; spaces are normed vector spaces. Let formula_1 be a measure space, let formula_2 and let formula_3 and formula_4 be elements of formula_5 Then formula_6 is in formula_7 and we have the triangle inequality

formula_8

with equality for formula_9 if and only if formula_3 and formula_4 are positively linearly dependent; that is, formula_12 for some formula_13 or formula_14 Here, the norm is given by:

formula_15

if formula_16 or in the case formula_17 by the essential supremum

formula_18

The Minkowski inequality is the triangle inequality in formula_5 In fact, it is a special case of the more general fact

formula_20

where it is easy to see that the right-hand side satisfies the triangular inequality.

Like Hölder&#x27;s inequality, the Minkowski inequality can be specialized to sequences and vectors by using the counting measure:

formula_21

for all real (or complex) numbers formula_22 and where formula_23 is the cardinality of formula_1 (the number of elements in formula_1).

In probabilistic terms, given the probability space formula_26 and formula_27 denote the expectation operator for every real- or complex-valued random variables formula_28 and formula_29 on formula_30 Minkowski&#x27;s inequality reads

:formula_31
The inequality is named after the German mathematician Hermann Minkowski.

